Basic Commands to Identify File Systems & Devices
1️⃣ lsblk – List block devices
lsblk
lsblk -f

Explanation

Shows disks, partitions, LVM, mount points.

-f displays filesystem type and UUID.

Example Output
sda
 ├─sda1  xfs   /boot
 ├─sda2  LVM2
     ├─rhel-root xfs /
     └─rhel-swap swap [SWAP]

2️⃣ fdisk – Partition information (MBR disks)
sudo fdisk -l

Explanation:

Lists disks, partitions, sizes, boot flags.

3️⃣ blkid – Identify filesystem type & UUID
sudo blkid

Explanation:

Shows filesystem type, UUID → used in /etc/fstab.

4️⃣ df – Show mounted filesystems & usage
df -h

Explanation:

Shows size, used, available space, mount points.

5️⃣ mount – Show mounted filesystems
mount | grep -v tmpfs

6️⃣ ls -l /dev/ – Identify block devices
ls -l /dev/sd*

7️⃣ Checking LVM devices
pvdisplay
vgdisplay
lvdisplay

8️⃣ Using file to identify filesystem
sudo file -s /dev/sda1

BASIC CONCEPT (Simple Explanation)
Mounting

Mounting means attaching a filesystem (disk/partition/ISO/NFS etc.) to a directory so the OS can access its files.

Example:
You attach /dev/sdb1 to /data → now /data shows the files inside /dev/sdb1.

Unmounting

Unmounting means detaching the disk/filesystem from the directory.

✅ 2. BASIC COMMANDS (Red Hat Style)
✔ Check available disks
lsblk

✔ Create a directory to mount
mkdir /mnt/mydisk

✔ Mount a disk
mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/mydisk

✔ Check mounted filesystems
mount | grep sdb1
df -h

✔ Unmount a filesystem
umount /mnt/mydisk
OR
umount /dev/sdb1

✔ Mount a filesystem permanently (fstab)

Edit:
vim /etc/fstab

Add entry:
/dev/sdb1  /data  xfs  defaults  0  0

Reload:
mount -a

